pan><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to identify </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">which features of academies might be causing improvement</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> (p2</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">0)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">simply</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">wide variations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> (p18). I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">mproved attainment had</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> not come from </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">academies’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">disadvantaged pupils  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">pp27-8);</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in fact the gap had risen (p6).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he apparent success of academies </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">depended</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> largely </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">on alternative qualifications (pp21-2).</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font