; font-size:12pt">The result was similar when </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">GNVQ </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Computing was compared with GCSE </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Maths</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Substituting</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> spuriously ‘equivalent’ qualifications is damaging to pupils for various reasons. They </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">probably</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> have less </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">‘street value’ than GCSEs, both in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">employmen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t and continuing education, and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> provide a poorer foundation for A-level. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Changing pupil populations</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Whatever the reasons, it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> is statistically irrefutable that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">poverty </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is associated with</span><sp